## Contemporary Political Corruption in the U.S.

Despite historical reforms, political corruption remains a significant concern in the U.S., with recent trends indicating a decline in resistance to corruption and increased public perception of corruption.

### Transparency International Corruption Perceptions Index (CPI)

| Year | U.S. CPI Rank (out of 180) | Notes                                  |
|-------|----------------------------|----------------------------------------|
| 2016  | 18                         | Higher resistance to corruption        |
| 2021  | 27                         | Decline in resistance; "countries to watch" status |

The U.S. dropped from 18th in 2016 to 27th in 2021 on the CPI, signaling increased perceived corruption ([Transparency International, 2021](https://www.transparency.org/en/cpi/2021/index/usa)).

### Public Perception and Survey Data

- **US Corruption Barometer 2017:**  
  - 44% of Americans believe corruption is pervasive in the White House (up from 36% in 2016).  
  - Nearly 70% believe the government is failing to fight corruption (up from 50% in 2016).  
  - 31% of African-Americans view the police as highly corrupt, compared to 20% overall.  
  - 55% cite fear of retaliation as a reason for not reporting corruption (up from 31% in 2016).  
  - 74% believe ordinary people can make a difference in fighting corruption ([Transparency International, 2017](https://www.transparency.org/en/news/corruption-in-the-usa-the-difference-a-year-makes)).

### Forms and Manifestations of Corruption

- **Political Influence and "Pay to Play":** Influence of wealthy individuals, revolving doors between government and private sector, and political spending opacity are key issues.

- **Law Enforcement Corruption:** Local and state police are more susceptible to corruption than federal agencies due to lower pay, less stringent hiring, and more discretionary authority. Corruption includes bribery, protecting illicit activities, and abuse of power ([eclecticme, 2016](https://discover.hubpages.com/politics/Police-Corruption-in-America)).

- **Tax Haven Status:** The U.S. has been cited as a tax haven, ranked second in the Financial Secrecy Index behind the Cayman Islands in 2020, with estimated offshore wealth of $800 billion ([Michel, 2020](https://www.vox.com/2020/2/3/21120076/us-tax-haven-global-kleptocracy)).

- **High-Profile Scandals:** Examples include the Trump administration's ethical controversies, the 2019 college admissions bribery scandal, and corporate failures linked to corruption ([Walt, 2019](https://www.businessinsider.com/us-corruption-problems-trump-boeing-college-admissions-2019-5)).

