## Government and Institutional Responses

### Investigative and Enforcement Agencies

- The FBI prioritizes public corruption as its top criminal investigative priority, conducting initiatives to investigate domestic and foreign corruption ([FBI, n.d.](https://www.fbi.gov/investigate/public-corruption)).

- The Department of Justice (DOJ) has a Public Integrity Section dedicated to prosecuting corruption cases.

### Legislative and Policy Measures

- **Corporate Transparency Act (2021):** Aims to increase transparency in corporate ownership to combat illicit finance.

- **United States Strategy on Countering Corruption (2021):** The Biden administration's first formal multi-departmental approach focusing on five pillars: modernizing efforts, curbing illicit finance, holding corrupt actors accountable, strengthening multilateral anti-corruption architecture, and improving diplomatic engagement ([Ropes & Gray LLP, 2021](https://www.ropesgray.com/en/newsroom/alerts/2021/12/United-States-Strategy-on-Countering-Corruption)).

### Challenges in Enforcement

- Corruption is deeply enmeshed in political and economic systems, making eradication complex.

- Informal norms traditionally curb corruption, but recent administrations have challenged these norms, exposing gaps in formal legal frameworks ([Stephenson, 2020](https://today.law.harvard.edu/a-history-of-corruption-in-the-united-states/)).

- Fear of retaliation inhibits whistleblowing and public reporting of corruption.

